[[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] <!--Kōbetsu--> [[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] <!--Kōbetsu--> [[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] <!--Kōbetsu--> [[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Kōbetsu]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] [[Category:qq]][[sn:Kōbetsu]][[Category:qq]] <!--Kōbetsu--> [[Category:Kōbetsu]][[ja:皇別氏族]] '''Kōbetsu''' (皇別) refers to the classification of Japanese clans that descended from the [[Imperial House of Japan]] through the [[demotion from imperial rank]] of collateral or cadet branches of the lineage after the reign of [[Emperor Jimmu]].{{sfn|Sato Yoshio|1994|p=36}}<ref>{{kotobank|Kōbetsu|Saeki Arikiyo, Encyclopedia of Japan}}</ref> This term was used in the genealogical register ''[[Shinsen Shōjiroku]]'', compiled by the [[Imperial Court (Japan)|Imperial Court]] in [[815 AD]] during the [[Kōnin era]]. It categorized clans into three groups: {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別}} (descendants of the [[Amatsukami]] and [[Kunitsukami]] deities), {{ill|Kōbetsu|ja|皇別}} (imperial descendants), and {{ill|Shoban|ja|諸蕃}} (descendants of immigrants from [[China]] and the [[Korean Peninsula]]). The Kōbetsu classification was also applied during the [[Meiji era]] under the [[kazoku]] system.{{sfn|Ueno Hideharu|2001|pp=37-38}}
== Overview == Kōbetsu clans emerged in ancient Japan, with powerful noble families like the [[Omi clan|Omi]], [[Katsuragi clan|Katsuragi]], and [[Soga clan|Soga]] tracing their lineage back to the imperial family. Scholar [[Saeki Arikiyo]] suggested that the classification of clans by origin began around the [[Taika Reform]] and that the system of three categories—"Kōbetsu, Shinbetsu, and Shoban"—may have been formalized by the [[Yatsuka no Kabane]] decree of [[Emperor Tenmu]].{{sfn|Sugazawa Yoko|2001|p=214}} Kōbetsu clans often used the kabane title [[Omi (kabane)|Omi]], although there were many exceptions, such as Kōbetsu clans with the kabane title [[Muraji]], and vice versa.{{sfn|Shinokawa Ken|2007|pp=50-51}}
