'''Kōbetsu''' (皇別) refers to the classification of Japanese clans that descended from the [[Imperial House of Japan]] through the {{ill|Demotion to subject status|ja|臣籍降下|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Demotion to subject status|qq=}} of collateral or cadet branches of the lineage after the reign of [[Emperor Jimmu]].{{sfn|Sato Yoshio|1994|p=36}}<ref>{{kotobank|Kōbetsu|Saeki Arikiyo, Encyclopedia of Japan}}</ref> This term was used in the genealogical register ''[[Shinsen Shōjiroku]]'', compiled by the [[Imperial Court (Japan)|Imperial Court]] in [[:en:815 AD|815 AD]] during the [[Kōnin era]]. It categorized clans into three groups: {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbetsu|qq=}} (descendants of the [[Amatsukami]] and [[Kunitsukami]] deities), {{ill|Kōbetsu|ja|皇別|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōbetsu|qq=}} (imperial descendants), and {{ill|Shoban|ja|諸蕃|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shoban|qq=}} (descendants of immigrants from [[China]] and the [[Korean Peninsula]]). The Kōbetsu classification was also applied during the [[Meiji era]] under the [[kazoku]] system.{{sfn|Ueno Hideharu|2001|pp=37-38}}

== Overview ==
Kōbetsu clans emerged in ancient Japan, with powerful noble families like the [[Omi clan|Omi]], [[Katsuragi clan|Katsuragi]], and [[Soga clan|Soga]] tracing their lineage back to the imperial family. Scholar [[Saeki Arikiyo]] suggested that the classification of clans by origin began around the [[Taika Reform]] and that the system of three categories—"Kōbetsu, Shinbetsu, and Shoban"—may have been formalized by the {{ill|Eight-Grade Rank System|ja|八色の姓|1=Eight Kabane system|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eight-Grade Rank System|13=User:Immanuelle/Eight Kabane system|qq=}} decree of [[Emperor Tenmu]].{{sfn|Sugazawa Yoko|2001|p=214}} Kōbetsu clans often used the kabane title [[Omi (kabane)|Omi]], although there were many exceptions, such as Kōbetsu clans with the kabane title [[Muraji]], and vice versa.{{sfn|Shinokawa Ken|2007|pp=50-51}}

These aristocratic clans saw their influence decline with the rise of the [[Fujiwara clan]] and the consolidation of imperial power. By the early [[Heian period]], most Kōbetsu clans had diminished to lower-Ranking [[kuge|nobility]] or local officials.{{sfn|Kuramoto Kazuhiro|2019|p=15}} Only a few clans, such as the [[Abe clan|Abe]] and [[Kii no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Ki]], maintained prominence. The ''Shinsen Shōjiroku'', compiled in [[:en:814 AD|814 AD]], originally listed clans in the order "Shinbetsu, Kōbetsu, and Shoban." However, in [[:en:815 AD|815 AD]], this order was revised to "Kōbetsu, Shinbetsu, and Shoban," reflecting changing perceptions of their significance.{{sfn|Sugazawa Yoko|2001|p=211}}

In the Heian period, financial constraints and succession disputes led to the practice of granting non-heir children of emperors and their concubines surnames, thus lowering their imperial Rank. For example, in [[:en:814 AD|814 AD]], Emperor [[Saga]] demoted eight of his children to subject status under the surname [[Minamoto clan|Minamoto]].{{sfn|Nakamura Midori|2015|pp=61}} These newly created [[Minamoto clan|Minamoto]] lines often struggled to maintain high status beyond the third generation. Most descendants either became low-Ranking nobles, provincial officials, or [[samurai]], while others disappeared from historical records.{{sfn|Kuramoto Kazuhiro|2019|p=15}}

=== Medieval to Early Modern Period ===
Kōbetsu clans that moved to the provinces often became influential samurai families. Notable examples include the [[Taira clan|Kanmu Taira]] and the [[Seiwa Genji]]. In the [[:en:9th century|9th century]], the Kanmu Taira's [[Taira no Masakado]] led the [[Tengyō no Ran]], and the [[Heike]] (Ise Taira) temporarily dominated the imperial court during the [[Heian period]]. The Seiwa Genji produced notable figures such as [[Minamoto no Yoritomo]], who established the [[Kamakura shogunate]], and [[Ashikaga Takauji]], the founder of the [[Muromachi shogunate]]. The [[Tokugawa clan]] also claimed descent from the Genji, although such claims were sometimes fabricated in later periods.{{sfn|Kuramoto Kazuhiro|2019|pp=124-132}}

=== Integration with Fujiwara Lineages ===
Some Fujiwara clans, originally classified as Shinbetsu, integrated imperial bloodlines through adoption or marriage. For example, the [[Konoe family|Konoe]], [[Ichijō family|Ichijō]], and [[Takatsukasa family|Takatsukasa]] branches were recognized as imperial descendants due to their close ties to the imperial family, occasionally earning the term "Kōbetsu Sesshō-ke" (imperial regent houses).{{sfn|Iwanami Yuko|2019|p=162}}

== Prominent Kōbetsu Clans ==
Below is a list of prominent Kōbetsu clans, categorized by period and kabane.

=== Asuka Period ===
* {{ill|Aso clan|ja|阿蘇君|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aso clan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 阿蘇氏}} (Kimi) – Descendants of Emperor Jimmu through [[:en:Kamuyaimimi|Kamuyatatehime]].
* [[:en:Ō clan|Ō clan]] (Asomi) – Descendants of Emperor Jimmu.
* {{ill|Tenji clan|ja|十市氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenji clan|qq=}} (Asomi) – Descendants of Emperor Annei.
* {{ill|Nitta clan|ja|新田部氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nitta clan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Sukune) – Descendants of Emperor Annei.
* [[:en:Wani clan|Wani clan]] (Omi) – Descendants of Emperor Kōshō.
* {{ill|Abe clan|ja|阿倍氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe clan|qq=}} (Asomi) – Descendants of Emperor Kōgen.
* [[:en:Katsuragi clan|Katsuragi clan]] (Omi) – Descendants of [[:en:Takenouchi no Sukune|Takenouchi no Sukune]].

=== Nara Period ===
* [[:en:Tachibana clan (kuge)|Tachibana clan]] (Sukune, later Asomi) – Descendants of Emperor Tenmu.
* {{ill|Fumi clan|ja|文室氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fumi clan|qq=}} (Manato) – Descendants of Emperor Tenmu.

=== Heian Period ===
* [[:en:Taira clan|Taira clan]] (Asomi) – Descendants of Emperor Kanmu.
* [[:en:Minamoto clan|Minamoto clan]] (Asomi) – Descendants of multiple emperors.

